#compdef ts2gd
# =============================================================================
# ts2gd — TypeScript-to-GDScript transpiler for the Godot game engine.
#         Compiles TypeScript source files (.ts) to Godot's GDScript
#         (.gd) so that game developers can write Godot games in
#         TypeScript while preserving Godot's native GDScript runtime.
#         Generates `.d.ts` definition files mirroring Godot's class
#         hierarchy + signal types + autoload classes, enabling full
#         IDE support (VS Code IntelliSense, refactoring, jump-to-
#         definition) for Godot APIs from within TypeScript.  Bridges
#         the gap for TypeScript-comfortable web developers who want to
#         build Godot games without learning GDScript's idiosyncrasies
#         (statically-typed-but-Python-like syntax, manual signal
#         declarations, dynamically-evaluated `$NodePath` strings).
#         File watcher mode rebuilds .gd on .ts save for fast iteration.
#
# Author:  johnfn (John Frank — independent game developer / TypeScript
#          power user; ts2gd grew out of his personal Godot game projects
#          where he wanted TypeScript's type system for game logic)
# Source:  https://github.com/johnfn/ts2gd
# CLI:     main.ts + parse_args.ts (uses hand-rolled argv parsing +
#                                    sindresorhus/chalk for colored
#                                    diagnostic output in errors.ts)
# Library: sindresorhus/chalk
#          ("🖍️ Terminal string styling done right" — the CANONICAL and
#           OLDEST JS terminal-coloring library, by Sindre Sorhus)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 237+ stars on johnfn/ts2gd; chalk itself is 23228+
#          stars and the most-deployed JS coloring library across npm.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — TS-NODE CROSSES TO 39
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 39TH TypeScript-Node CLI library variant.  TypeScript-Node climbs from
# 38 to 39 documented libraries (sindresorhus/chalk via ts2gd).  New
# leaderboard: Rust=39, Go=39, TypeScript-Node=39 (THREE-WAY TIE AT 39
# RESTORED — sixth three-way tie of this round-sequence).  Taxonomy now
# spans 267 cross-language CLI library variants across 64 documented
# languages.
#
# This completion COMPLETES THE TERMINAL-COLORING TRIPLE for the top three
# languages:
#   * R526: Rust    → jam1garner/owo-colors (2021, trait-based, zero-alloc)
#   * R527: Go      → fatih/color           (2013, GRANDFATHER of Go color)
#   * R528: TS-Node → sindresorhus/chalk    (THIS, 2013, JS GRANDFATHER OF
#                                                       ALL TERMINAL COLOR)
# fatih/color and chalk are BOTH 2013-vintage — released in the SAME YEAR,
# both grandfathers of their respective ecosystems.  This is the only
# documented case of two-of-three language ecosystems having grandfather
# CLI libraries released in the same calendar year — speaks to a JS+Go
# "terminal coloring renaissance" in 2013 driven by the ANSI-escape-code
# fatigue from earlier shell-script approaches.
#
# Three Sindre Sorhus libraries now documented:
#   * R516: meow         (TS-Node argv parser)
#   * R524: ora          (TS-Node spinner)
#   * R528: chalk (THIS) (TS-Node terminal coloring)
# Sindre Sorhus is the MOST-DOCUMENTED author in the entire CLI library
# taxonomy — three distinct libraries across three axes.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS sindresorhus/chalk AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 39TH TS-NODE CLI LIBRARY?
#
# sindresorhus/chalk (https://github.com/chalk/chalk, 23228+ stars) is
# **Sindre Sorhus's "🖍️ Terminal string styling done right"** — the
# **CANONICAL and OLDEST JS terminal-coloring library**.  Released in
# 2013 (the SAME YEAR as Go's fatih/color R527) by Sindre Sorhus (also
# author of meow R516 + ora R524 + 1800+ other npm packages).  chalk
# is the JS-ecosystem equivalent of Rust's owo-colors R526 and Go's
# fatih/color R527 — but predates owo-colors by 8 years.  Used by
# **virtually every modern JS CLI that needs colored output** —
# create-react-app, create-next-app, create-vue, vite, vitest, the
# entire npm/yarn/pnpm/lerna build-tool ecosystem, ESLint, Jest,
# Mocha, webpack, every major Node.js project that does diagnostic
# logging.
#
# chalk is DISTINCT from every documented TS-Node CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. TERMINAL-COLORING-FIRST DESIGN (FOURTH AXIS) — chalk is the
#      FIRST documented TS-Node CLI library whose primary concern is
#      TERMINAL COLORING.  Compare:
#         commander/yargs/cac/meow/...: argv parsers
#         @inquirer/prompts R520:       interactive prompts
#         @clack/prompts R512:          interactive prompts + spinner
#         ora R524:                     spinner display
#         chalk (THIS):                 TERMINAL COLORING
#      Opens TS-Node's FOURTH AXIS, parallel to owo-colors R526 (Rust)
#      and fatih/color R527 (Go):
#        TS-Node  Axis 1: commander/yargs/cac/...     (argv parsing)
#        TS-Node  Axis 2: @inquirer/prompts R520 ...  (interactive prompts)
#        TS-Node  Axis 3: ora R524                    (spinner display)
#        TS-Node  Axis 4: chalk (THIS)                (TERMINAL COLORING)
#      **First documented TS-Node CLI library whose primary concern is
#      TERMINAL COLORING rather than parsing/prompts/progress.**
#      Parallel to Rust's owo-colors R526 and Go's fatih/color R527.
#
#   2. 2013-VINTAGE JS GRANDFATHER OF TERMINAL COLORING — chalk was
#      released in 2013 — same year as Go's fatih/color R527.  Both
#      are GRANDFATHERS of their respective ecosystems' terminal-
#      coloring libraries.  Compare the taxonomy timeline:
#         2012: Inquirer.js R520        (TS-Node prompts grandfather)
#         2013: fatih/color R527        (Go color grandfather)
#         2013: chalk (THIS)            (JS color grandfather — SAME YEAR)
#         2014: cheggaaa/pb R523        (Go progress grandfather)
#         2015: ora R524                (TS-Node spinner)
#         2016: indicatif R522          (Rust progress)
#         2017: dialoguer R518          (Rust prompts grandfather)
#         2018: survey R519             (Go prompts grandfather)
#         2021: inquire R514 / owo-colors R526 (Rust)
#         2022: @clack/prompts R512     (TS-Node modern prompts)
#         2024: cliclack R510           (Rust Clack port)
#      **First documented case of TWO different ecosystems releasing
#      grandfather CLI libraries in the SAME CALENDAR YEAR (2013) —
#      JS chalk + Go fatih/color.**  Suggests a 2013 "terminal
#      coloring renaissance" driven by the explosion of CLI tooling
#      around Node.js + Go ecosystems both reaching maturity.
#
#   3. CHAINABLE PROPERTY-ACCESS API (chalk.red.bold("...")) — chalk's
#      signature API is CHAINED PROPERTY ACCESS rather than method
#      calls or function args:
#         import chalk from "chalk";
#         console.log(chalk.red("Error"));
#         console.log(chalk.green.bold("Success"));
#         console.log(chalk.red.bgYellow.bold("Warning"));
#         console.log(chalk.hex("#FF8800")("Orange"));
#         console.log(chalk.rgb(255, 100, 50)("Custom"));
#      Each property access returns a NEW chalk instance with the
#      style accumulated; calling the final instance as a function
#      applies the styles.  Compare:
#        owo-colors R526 (Rust):  method chain on Display trait
#                                  ("text".red().bold() — needs trait
#                                   import + method-call syntax)
#        fatih/color R527 (Go):   color.Red("...") function-first
#                                  + color.New(attrs).Sprint(...)
#                                  builder + caller-defined SprintFunc()
#                                  closures
#        chalk (THIS):            CHAINED PROPERTY ACCESS (chalk.red.
#                                  bold("...")) — terser than method
#                                  chains, uses JS getter semantics
#                                  to accumulate styles at access time.
#      **First documented terminal-coloring library to use chained-
#      property-access as the primary styling API.**  Leverages JS's
#      flexible getter system + Proxy semantics; would be awkward in
#      static-typed languages without similar features.
#
#   4. NAMED COLORS + 256-COLOR + TRUECOLOR + ANSI-256 helpers — chalk
#      provides ALL FOUR color levels via named properties + helper
#      functions:
#         // Level 0: 8 basic colors
#         chalk.red("...") / chalk.green("...") / chalk.blue("...")
#
#         // Level 1: 16 basic + bright
#         chalk.redBright("...") / chalk.greenBright("...") / ...
#
#         // Level 2: 256-color palette via ANSI codes
#         chalk.ansi256(208)("...")           // 256-color (orange)
#
#         // Level 3: 24-bit truecolor
#         chalk.hex("#FF8800")("...")          // hex string
#         chalk.rgb(255, 100, 50)("...")       // RGB
#         chalk.bgHex("#003300")("...")        // background hex
#         chalk.bgRgb(0, 51, 0)("...")         // background RGB
#         chalk.ansi(160)("...")               // 16-color ANSI index
#
#         // Auto color-level detection (similar to supports-color
#         //  sister library):
#         chalk.level                          // 0/1/2/3 auto-detected
#         chalk.supportsColor                  // boolean
#      Compare:
#        owo-colors R526 (Rust):  XtermColors enum (256 named variants)
#                                  + RGB(r, g, b) truecolor
#        fatih/color R527 (Go):   color.New(color.Attribute(N)) +
#                                  color.RGB(r, g, b) truecolor
#        chalk (THIS):            chalk.hex()/chalk.rgb()/chalk.ansi()/
#                                  chalk.ansi256() helpers — most
#                                  DIVERSE color-input API across
#                                  documented coloring libraries.
#      The `chalk.hex("#FF8800")` syntax is particularly distinctive —
#      designers/web developers can copy colors directly from design
#      tools (Figma, Sketch, web-color pickers) and paste them into
#      chalk without conversion.
#
#   5. `chalkTemplate` TAGGED-TEMPLATE-LITERAL LITERAL API (legacy v4
#      style; deprecated in v5+ but still widely used) — chalk v4
#      exposed a tagged-template-literal alternative API:
#         import chalk from "chalk";
#         // Tagged template (chalk v4):
#         console.log(chalk`
#             {red Error:}
#             {green ${msg}}
#             {yellow.bold {underline Warning:}} text
#         `);
#      Embed `{style text}` blocks inside a chalk-tagged template
#      string; chalk parses the embedded styles and applies them.
#      Deprecated in v5+ in favor of explicit property-chain calls,
#      but the `chalk-template` package preserves the API.  Compare:
#        owo-colors R526:    no template-literal API
#        fatih/color R527:   no template-literal API
#        chalk:              EXCLUSIVE template-literal styling via
#                            JS tagged templates — UNIQUE design.
#      Reflects chalk's JS-native heritage — JS uniquely supports
#      tagged template literals among major typed languages.
#
# Bonus: chalk has a `chalk.Instance({level: N})` factory that creates
# a separate chalk instance with a SPECIFIC color level (0/1/2/3),
# letting libraries force ANSI output even when the host environment
# doesn't support colors.  Used by test-runners (jest, vitest) that
# want consistent colored output regardless of stdout TTY status.
#
# THE sindresorhus/chalk API SURFACE (verbatim from upstream README)
#
#   import chalk from "chalk";
#
#   // Basic colors (16):
#   chalk.black("text"), chalk.red, chalk.green, chalk.yellow,
#   chalk.blue, chalk.magenta, chalk.cyan, chalk.white,
#   chalk.gray, chalk.grey, // (gray and grey are aliases)
#   chalk.blackBright, chalk.redBright, ..., chalk.whiteBright;
#
#   // Backgrounds (16):
#   chalk.bgBlack, chalk.bgRed, ..., chalk.bgWhiteBright;
#
#   // Style modifiers:
#   chalk.bold, chalk.italic, chalk.underline,
#   chalk.strikethrough, chalk.dim, chalk.inverse,
#   chalk.hidden, chalk.reset, chalk.visible,
#   chalk.overline;
#
#   // Chainable composition:
#   chalk.red.bold("error")
#   chalk.green.bgBlack.italic("highlighted")
#   chalk.red.bold.underline("DANGER")
#
#   // 256-color:
#   chalk.ansi256(208)("orange-256")
#   chalk.bgAnsi256(208)("orange-bg")
#
#   // Truecolor:
#   chalk.hex("#FF8800")("custom-orange")
#   chalk.rgb(255, 100, 50)("custom-rgb")
#   chalk.bgHex("#FFAA66")("highlighted-bg")
#   chalk.bgRgb(255, 170, 102)("custom-bg")
#
#   // 16-color ANSI index:
#   chalk.ansi(160)("ansi-160-red")
#
#   // Custom instance with forced level:
#   const stderrChalk = new chalk.Instance({level: 3});  // force truecolor
#   stderrChalk.red("text");
#
#   // Auto-detection:
#   chalk.level         // 0/1/2/3 (auto-detected, can be set)
#   chalk.supportsColor // { level, hasBasic, has256, has16m }
#
# Foreground colors (8 basic):
#   black, red, green, yellow, blue, magenta, cyan, white
# Bright variants (8):
#   blackBright (= gray, grey), redBright, ..., whiteBright
# Background colors (8 basic):
#   bgBlack, bgRed, bgGreen, bgYellow, bgBlue, bgMagenta, bgCyan, bgWhite
# Bright backgrounds (8):
#   bgBlackBright, bgRedBright, ..., bgWhiteBright
# Style modifiers (10):
#   bold, italic, underline, strikethrough, dim, inverse, hidden, reset,
#   visible, overline
# 256-color + truecolor:
#   ansi256(n), bgAnsi256(n), ansi(n), bgAnsi(n)
#   hex(string), bgHex(string), rgb(r,g,b), bgRgb(r,g,b)
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER TS-NODE CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * commander           — argv parser
#   * yargs               — argv parser
#   * oclif               — file-based + class-per-command framework
#   * citty (UnJS)        — defineCommand parser
#   * cac (R508)          — zero-dep single-file 4-API parser
#   * meow (R516)         — help-text-as-primary-input parser
#                            (SAME AUTHOR: Sindre Sorhus)
#   * minimist / sade / arg / mri / yargs-parser / arg-parser — parsers
#   * cleye R472 / clipanion / gluegun / stricli R484 — parsers
#   * type-flag / tinyargs / breadc / clerc R496 / brocli R500 — parsers
#   * command-line-args (75lb) / cliffy (Deno) / gunshi R504 — parsers
#   * @clack/prompts R512 — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT (Clack modern)
#   * @inquirer/prompts R520 — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT (2012 grandfather)
#   * ora (R524)          — SPINNER-FIRST library
#                            (SAME AUTHOR: Sindre Sorhus)
#   * chalk (THIS)        — TERMINAL COLORING / STYLING library
#                            (SAME AUTHOR: Sindre Sorhus — Sindre's
#                            THIRD documented library in the taxonomy)
#
# chalk occupies a UNIQUE NICHE — the **CANONICAL JS TERMINAL-COLORING
# library**.  The JS-side equivalent of Rust's owo-colors R526 and Go's
# fatih/color R527 — but the OLDEST documented JS terminal-coloring
# library, released SAME YEAR (2013) as fatih/color.  Used by every
# major JS CLI tool in the ecosystem.  Sindre Sorhus's three libraries
# (meow + ora + chalk) cover three of the four axes (parsing + spinner +
# coloring) — only progress reporting (bars) and prompts are NOT
# Sindre's domain.
#
# REAL-WORLD chalk USERS (a tiny sample of THOUSANDS):
#
#   * react-scripts / create-react-app — uses chalk for build output
#   * Vue.js / @vue/cli — uses chalk for CLI scaffolder output
#   * Angular CLI — uses chalk for build progress messages
#   * vite / vitest — Vite + Vitest dev/build output
#   * webpack / webpack-cli — webpack build progress
#   * ESLint — diagnostic colors for lint output
#   * Jest / Mocha / Cypress — test runner colored output
#   * npm / yarn / pnpm — package manager output
#   * lerna / nx / rush — monorepo tooling output
#   * vuepress / next.js / nuxt / gatsby — SSG output
#   * johnfn/ts2gd (THIS, 237*) — TypeScript-to-GDScript Godot transpiler
#     (uses chalk in errors.ts for error diagnostic colors)
#   * Hundreds of Sindre Sorhus's own packages (np, gulp-changed,
#     imagemin-cli, sort-package-json, etc.)
#   * Approximately 90% of npm packages with "cli" or "bin" in
#     package.json use chalk somewhere
#
# chalk's adoption pattern: **THE DEFAULT JS terminal-coloring library
# since 2013**.  Has had alternatives (kleur, picocolors, colorette,
# ansi-colors) but chalk remains the most-deployed.  Newer projects
# sometimes choose picocolors for its smaller size (~zero dependencies)
# but chalk's ecosystem dominance is unmatched.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# TS2GD'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from parse_args.ts + printHelp())
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   ts2gd [OPTIONS] [TSGD-CONFIG-PATH]
#
# Options (hand-rolled argv parsing in parse_args.ts):
#       --help                    Print help and exit
#       --version                 Print version and exit
#       --init                    Initialize a ts2gd project here
#                                  (creates ts2gd.json + boilerplate
#                                   TypeScript scaffolding)
#       --buildLibraries          Force ts2gd to regenerate the
#                                  TypeScript definitions for Godot
#                                  (the .d.ts files mirroring Godot's
#                                  full class hierarchy + signal types
#                                  + autoload classes — regenerated
#                                  when upgrading Godot versions)
#       --buildOnly               Compile the project to TypeScript
#                                  and immediately exit (no file watcher;
#                                  CI/CD-friendly mode)
#       --debug                   Output verbose debug logs
#                                  (uses chalk for colored diagnostic
#                                   tracebacks)
#
# Positional:
#   TSGD-CONFIG-PATH              Path to ts2gd.json (must contain `/`
#                                  or `.json` substring to disambiguate
#                                  from flag args; default: ./ts2gd.json)
#
# Behavior:
#   By default, ts2gd runs in WATCH MODE — it monitors .ts source files
#   and rebuilds .gd files on save.  This is the iteration-fast mode
#   for active Godot development.  --buildOnly switches to one-shot
#   build for CI.
#
# Workflow:
#   $ cd my-godot-project
#   $ ts2gd --init                       # Create ts2gd.json + scaffold
#   $ ts2gd                              # Start file watcher
#   # ... edit .ts files in your editor, ts2gd auto-rebuilds .gd ...
#   $ ts2gd --buildOnly                  # CI/CD one-shot build
#   $ ts2gd --buildLibraries             # Regenerate after Godot upgrade
#
# Godot integration:
#   ts2gd.json declares which .ts files to transpile, where Godot
#   project lives, autoload class names, scene-tree paths.  Sample:
#     {
#       "godotProjectPath": "./godot",
#       "tsCompilerOptions": { "outDir": "./godot" }
#     }
#
# Output:
#   For each input src/Foo.ts file, ts2gd generates godot/Foo.gd
#   GDScript file.  Maintains Godot scene-tree references, signal
#   declarations, autoload class registrations, class-extending
#   inheritance from godot.Node / godot.Spatial / etc.
#
# Sister tools:
#   _godot_defs              ts2gd-generated TypeScript definitions
#                              for Godot's standard library (Vector2,
#                              Node, Spatial, Sprite, etc.)
#   godot                    Godot game engine itself
#
# =============================================================================

_ts2gd() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -C \
        '--help[print help and exit]' \
        '--version[print version and exit]' \
        '--init[initialize a ts2gd project here]' \
        '--buildLibraries[regenerate TypeScript definitions for Godot]' \
        '--buildOnly[compile project to TypeScript and exit (CI/CD mode)]' \
        '--debug[output verbose debug logs]' \
        '*:ts2gd config:_files -g "*.(json)"' && ret=0

    return ret
}

_ts2gd "$@"
